Setting Up

For this milestone, you will:

  • Finalize hypotheses
  • Run two of your final analyses & interpret the results
  • Create a visualization for each of your hypothesis results
  • Create a table for each of your hypothesis results

For this key, I will use the palmerpenguins dataset to complete the exercises.

My advice to you: look over your Milestone 1 and any comments I left for you on the assignment.

Research Questions

EXERCISE 2: Finalize your Research Questions & Hypotheses

For the final project you will run 4 analyses: a correlation, a t-test, and 2 different multiple regressions.

If I did not leave any feedback/suggestions for you to change your research questions & you want to keep them, you can use the exact same ones from Milestone 1. Make sure to add a hypothesis.

Correlation Research Question: Come up with a correlation research question. As a reminder, a correlation looks at the relationship between two numeric variables. What are two numeric variables that you think could be related? In what way would they be related?

Question: Are bill length and bill depth positively related? Both are independent variables.

Hypothesis: I hypothesize that bill length and bill depth will be positively correlated with eachother.

T-Test Research Question: Come up with a t-test research question. A t-test compares two different groups on a numeric variables. For example, I could look at if there is a difference in male versus female penguins (independent variable) on how much they weigh (dependent variable). My research question would be: Do male penguins weigh more than female penguins? T-Tests can only compare two different groups (not 3+).

Question: Do male penguins weigh more than female penguins? Penguin sex is the independent variable. Penguin weight is the dependent variable.

Hypothesis: I hypothesize that male penguins weigh more than female penguins.

Multiple Regression Research Questions: Come up with two different multiple regression research questions. A regression as a numeric variable as a dependent variable. A Multiple regression is a regression that has 2 or more independent variables. I suggest sticking only to 2 or three independent variables. For example, I could look at if penguin species (independent variable 1) and penguin island (independent variable 2) impact penguin body mass (dependent variable).

Question 1: Do penguin species (independent variable 1) and penguin island (independent variable 2) impact penguin body mass (dependent variable)?

Hypothesis: I hypothesize that Gentoo penguins from Biscoe island will be the heaviest penguins.

Question 2: Do penguin species (independent variable 1) and penguin island (independent variable 2) impact penguin flipper length (dependent variable)?

Hypothesis: I hypothesize that Adelie penguins from Dream Island will have the longest flippers.

Analyses

For this milestone you must run two of your final analyses. For example, you can run a correlation and a t-test, or two multiple regressions, or any other combinaton of analyses. For this key I will be running all 4 analyses.

Analysis 1

EXERCISE 4: Run Your Analysis

For my first analysis I will run a correlation.

Note: After you run the correlation, interpret the results in APA format.

cor.test(penguins$bill_length_mm, penguins$bill_depth_mm)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  penguins$bill_length_mm and penguins$bill_depth_mm
## t = -4.4591, df = 340, p-value = 1.12e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3328072 -0.1323004
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.2350529

There is a significant negative correlation between the bill depth and bill length of penguins, r(340) = -.24, p < .001.

EXERCISE 5: Graphing

Now, create a graph for the analysis you just ran.

I just ran a correlation and therefore I will create a scatterplot.

ggplot(penguins, aes(bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Bill Length", y = "Bill Depth", title = " Flipper Length x Depth")

EXERCISE 6: Visualization Interpretation

Next, create a table for the analysis you just ran.

Analysis 2

EXERCISE 8: Run Your Analysis

For my second analysis I will run a t-test.

Note: After you run the t-test, interpret the results in APA format.

t.test(body_mass_g ~ sex, penguins)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  body_mass_g by sex
## t = -8.5545, df = 323.9, p-value = 4.794e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group female and group male is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -840.5783 -526.2453
## sample estimates:
## mean in group female   mean in group male 
##             3862.273             4545.685

There is a significant difference between the weight of male versus female penguins, with male penguins weighing more, t(323.9) = -8.55, p < .001.

EXERCISE 9: Graphing

Now, create a graph for the analysis you just ran.

I just ran a t-test and therefore I will create a bar graph.

ggplot(penguins %>% filter(!is.na(sex)), aes(sex, body_mass_g, fill = sex)) +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "bar", position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal()  +
  labs(x = "Penguin Sex", y = "Body Mass", title = "Body Mass by Sex") +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako")

EXERCISE 10: Visualization Interpretation

In the space below, write 1-2 sentences interpreting what you learned from the the previous graph.

EXERCISE 11: Table

Next, create a table for the analysis you just ran.

For a t-test, we will want to create a table showing the means and sd of male versus female penguins on body mass.

penguins %>%
  filter(!is.na(sex)) %>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarize(Mean = mean(body_mass_g, na.rm = T),
            SD = sd(body_mass_g, na.rm = T))%>%
  kable(booktabs = TRUE)
sex Mean SD
female 3862.273 666.1720
male 4545.685 787.6289

Bonus Analysis 3

Run Your Analysis

For my third analysis I will run a multiple regression.

Note: After you run the regression, interpret the results in APA format.

#Do penguin species (independent variable 1) and penguin island (independent variable 2) impact penguin body mass (dependent variable)?

#I hypothesize that Gentoo penguins from Biscoe island will be the heaviest penguins.

penguins$species <- relevel(penguins$species, ref = "Gentoo")

mod.1 <- lm(body_mass_g ~ species*island, penguins)
summary(mod.1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = body_mass_g ~ species * island, data = penguins)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -1126.02  -333.09   -33.09   316.91  1223.98 
## 
## Coefficients: (4 not defined because of singularities)
##                                   Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                       5076.016     41.801 121.432   <2e-16 ***
## speciesAdelie                    -1366.357     81.437 -16.778   <2e-16 ***
## speciesChinstrap                 -1321.662    116.750 -11.320   <2e-16 ***
## islandDream                        -21.266     93.395  -0.228    0.820    
## islandTorgersen                     -3.287     95.388  -0.034    0.973    
## speciesAdelie:islandDream               NA         NA      NA       NA    
## speciesChinstrap:islandDream            NA         NA      NA       NA    
## speciesAdelie:islandTorgersen           NA         NA      NA       NA    
## speciesChinstrap:islandTorgersen        NA         NA      NA       NA    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 463.6 on 337 degrees of freedom
##   (2 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6697, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6658 
## F-statistic: 170.8 on 4 and 337 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

There are no significant interactions between species and island on body mass (p’s > 0.05). There is also no main effect of Biscoe island (p’s > 0.05). There is a significant main effect of species such that Gentoo penguins are heavier than both Adelie (b = -1366.357, SE = 81.437, p < 0.05) and Chinstrap penguins (b = -1321.662, SE = 116.750, p < 0.05).

Graphing

Now, create a graph for the analysis you just ran.

I just ran a t-test and therefore I will create a bar graph.

ggplot(penguins, aes(species, body_mass_g, fill = island)) +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "bar", position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal()  +
  labs(x = "Penguin Species", y = "Body Mass", fill = "Penguin Island", title = "Body Mass by Species x Island") +

Bonus Analysis 4

Run Your Analysis

For my fourth analysis I will run a multiple regression.

Note: After you run the regression, interpret the results in APA format.

#**Question 2:** Do penguin species (independent variable 1) and penguin island (independent variable 2) impact penguin flipper length (dependent variable)?

#**Hypothesis:** I hypothesize that Adelie penguins from Dream Island will have the longest flippers.

penguins$species <- relevel(penguins$species, ref = "Adelie")
penguins$island <- relevel(penguins$island, ref = "Dream")


mod.2 <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ species*island, penguins)
summary(mod.2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ species * island, data = penguins)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.8235  -4.7321  -0.1961   4.1975  18.8039 
## 
## Coefficients: (4 not defined because of singularities)
##                                  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                      189.7321     0.8859 214.157  < 2e-16 ***
## speciesGentoo                     28.3915     1.1646  24.378  < 2e-16 ***
## speciesChinstrap                   6.0914     1.1964   5.092 5.92e-07 ***
## islandBiscoe                      -0.9367     1.3356  -0.701    0.484    
## islandTorgersen                    1.4639     1.2833   1.141    0.255    
## speciesGentoo:islandBiscoe             NA         NA      NA       NA    
## speciesChinstrap:islandBiscoe          NA         NA      NA       NA

## speciesChinstrap:islandTorgersen       NA         NA      NA       NA    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 6.63 on 337 degrees of freedom
##   (2 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7803, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7777 
## F-statistic: 299.2 on 4 and 337 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

There are no significant interactions between species and island on flipper length (p’s > 0.05). There is also no main effect of Drean island (p’s > 0.05). There is a significant main effect of species such that Adelie penguins have shorter flippers than both Gentoo (b = 28.3915, SE = 1.1646, p < 0.05) and Chinstrap penguins (b = 6.0914, SE = 1.1964, p < 0.05).
